prior_check

Model goal

Measure the difference between two conditions, for each subject.

The likelihood for the model is always.

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathrm{-likelihood-} \\ error_i &\sim (1-p\_guess_i)*VM(0, \kappa_i) + (p\_guess_i)*Unif(0,2\pi) \\ \\ \mathrm{-param~transformation-} \\ \kappa_i &= sd2k(circ\_sd_i) \\ \end{aligned} \]

The centered parameterization of the linear model would be:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathrm{-linear~model-} \\ circ\_sd_i &= exp(\alpha_{0,SUBJ[i]} + \alpha_{\Delta,SUBJ[i]} * postCond) ~~ \mathrm{-log~link~on~sd-} \\ p\_guess_i &= inv\_logit(\beta_{0,SUBJ[i]} + \beta_{\Delta,SUBJ[i]} * postCond) ~~ \mathrm{-logit~link~on~p\_guess-} \\ \\ \mathrm{-priors:~all~independent-}\\ \alpha_{0,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(mu\_\alpha_0, sigma\_\alpha_0) \\ \alpha_{\Delta,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(mu\_\alpha_{\Delta}, sigma\_\alpha_{\Delta}) \\ \beta_{0,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(mu\_\beta_0, sigma\_\beta_0) \\ \beta_{\Delta,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(mu\_\beta_{\Delta}, sigma\_\beta_{\Delta}) \\ \\ mu\_\alpha_0 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\alpha_0 &\sim dist(?) \\ mu\_\alpha_{\Delta} &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\alpha_{\Delta} &\sim dist(?)\\ mu\_\beta_0 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\beta_0 &\sim dist(?)\\ mu\_\beta_{\Delta} &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\beta_{\Delta} &\sim dist(?)\\ \end{aligned} \]

The actual model Ill fit, the non-centered parameterization in brms, will look more like:

\[ \begin{aligned} \mathrm{-linear~model-} \\ circ\_sd_i &= exp(\alpha_1 + \alpha_{1,SUBJ[i]} + (\alpha_2 + \alpha_{2,SUBJ[i]}) * postCond) ~~ \mathrm{-log~link~on~sd-} \\ p\_guess_i &= inv\_logit(\beta_1 + \beta_{1,SUBJ[i]} + (\beta_2 + \beta_{2,SUBJ[i]}) * postCond) ~~ \mathrm{-logit~link~on~p\_guess-} \\ \\ \mathrm{-priors:~all~independent-}\\ \alpha_{1,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(0, sigma\_\alpha_1) \\ \alpha_{2,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(0, sigma\_\alpha_2) \\ \beta_{1,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(0, sigma\_\beta_1) \\ \beta_{2,SUBJ[...]} &\sim Normal(0, sigma\_\beta_2) \\ \\ \alpha_1 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\alpha_1 &\sim dist(?) \\ \alpha_2 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\alpha_2 &\sim dist(?)\\ \beta_1 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\beta_1 &\sim dist(?)\\ \beta_2 &\sim dist(?)\\ sigma\_\beta_2 &\sim dist(?)\\ \end{aligned} \]

Ive kept the sigma parameters in the prior notation, when really they should be moved to the linear model and the priors set to \(Normal(0,1)\).

The purpose of this document is to figure out reasonable values for those priors, both super uninformative and weakly informative.

Priors on slope and intercept with log link

I know that circ_sd should stay between ~20 and ~180. This would be very weakly informative.

my_deg2rad <- function(d){
  #/180
  return(d * (pi/180))
}
my_deg2rad_vec <- Vectorize(my_deg2rad)

#helper functions
sd2k <- function(sd_input) {
  
  #sd_input needs to be radians

  #original matlab code
  # R <- exp(-S.^2/2);
  # K = 1./(R.^3 - 4 * R.^2 + 3 * R);
  # K(R < 0.85) = -0.4 + 1.39 * R(R < 0.85) + 0.43./(1 - R(R < 0.85));
  # K(R < 0.53) = 2 * R(R < 0.53) + R(R < 0.53).^3 + (5 * R(R < 0.53).^5)/6;

  R <- exp(-(sd_input^2)/2)
  K <- 1/((R^3) - (4 * R^2) + (3*R))
  
  if(R < 0.85){
    K <- -0.4 + (1.39 * R) + (0.43/(1-R))
  }
  
  if(R < 0.53){
    K <- (2 * R) + R^3 + (5 * R^5)/6
  }
  

  return(K)
}
sd2k_vec <- Vectorize(sd2k)

#helper functions
sim_vm <- function(k){
  res <- Rfast::rvonmises(1, pi, k, rads = TRUE)
  return(res[1])
}
sim_vm_vec <- Vectorize(sim_vm)

Placing too much mass below zero in link-space will place loads of mass at zero in de-linked space.

For example a uniform prior \(Unif(-5, 5)\) results in a pile of mass on zero.

unif_prior_sim <- 
  tibble("unif_draws" = runif(1e4, -5, 5)) %>%
  mutate("exp_output" = exp(unif_draws))

ggplot(unif_prior_sim, aes(x = exp_output)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 2)

Try a normal prior

lnorm_prior_sim <-
  tibble("prior" = rnorm(5e4, 4, 0.5)) %>%
  mutate(log_link_prior = exp(prior), log_link_prior_k = sd2k_vec(deg2rad(log_link_prior)), implied_data_rad = map(log_link_prior_k, sim_vm)) %>%
  unnest(implied_data_rad)

hist_quantile <- round(quantile(lnorm_prior_sim$prior, c(0.05, 0.95)), 2)
prior_hist <- 
  ggplot(lnorm_prior_sim, aes(x = prior)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = hist_quantile) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 15)) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0, 10)) 

hist_quantile <- round(quantile(lnorm_prior_sim$log_link_prior, c(0.05, 0.95)), 2)
delink_prior_hist <- 
  ggplot(lnorm_prior_sim, aes(x = log_link_prior)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = hist_quantile) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 15)) + 
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0, 300)) 

prior_cdf <- 
  ggplot(lnorm_prior_sim, aes(x = log_link_prior)) + 
  stat_ecdf() + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 15)) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0, 300)) 
  #geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)

data_hist <-

  scale_x_continuous(breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10)) +

plot_grid(prior_hist, delink_prior_hist, prior_cdf, data_hist, ncol = 1, align = "v")

Notes:

skew-normal is a little unnecessary.

good prior on group mean = Normal(4, 0.5).

good prior on group delta = Normal(0, 0.5). Potentially constrain it to 0.3

Now check prior on p_mem difference

prior(normal(0, 1.5), class = b, coef = intercept, dpar = theta) +

prior(normal(0, 1.5), class = b, coef = stimulation, dpar = theta)

norm_prior_sim <-

  mutate(logit_link_prior_pre = exp(prior_pre)/(1 + exp(prior_pre)),
